An advanced analysis of Carbon–Carbon double bond stretching in Infrared (IR) spectroscopy can be framed using the harmonic oscillator model for vibrational modes. Consider two structurally similar alkenes (identical isotopic composition, no mass differences in the atoms participating in the Carbon–Carbon stretch) whose isolated Carbon–Carbon double bond stretching bands are observed at wavenumbers $	ilde{
u}_{\mathrm{A}}=1620\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}}$ and $	ilde{
u}_{\mathrm{B}}=1680\ \mathrm{cm^{-1}}$, respectively. Both absorptions are clean, unperturbed fundamentals with negligible coupling to other modes and no significant Fermi resonance.

Starting from the harmonic oscillator description of bond stretching and the definition of wavenumber $	ilde{
u}$ in terms of the vibrational frequency and the speed of light, justify which alkene is more conjugated based on the physical effect of $\pi$-electron delocalization on the effective force constant $k$ of the Carbon–Carbon double bond. Under the assumption that the reduced mass $\mu$ of the vibrating pair is the same in both alkenes, derive the relationship between the ratio of wavenumbers and the ratio of force constants, and compute the fractional decrease in the force constant of the more conjugated alkene relative to the less conjugated alkene. Express your final result as a dimensionless decimal fraction, and round your answer to four significant figures. Do not include a percent sign in your answer.

A carbon–carbon triple bond stretch in Infrared (IR) spectroscopy can be modeled as a single vibrational normal mode approximated by a harmonic oscillator embedded in a polyatomic molecule. Under the Born–Oppenheimer approximation, isotopic substitution changes the masses but not the electronic potential, so the local curvature of the potential (the effective force constant) for the $\mathrm{C\equiv C}$ stretching mode is assumed unchanged by isotope substitution. Starting from classical mechanics for two point masses connected by a spring and the quantum harmonic oscillator treatment of molecular vibrations, derive the dependence of the fundamental vibrational wavenumber $	ilde{
u}$ on the reduced mass $\mu$. Use this to quantify the isotopic effect when one atom of the $\mathrm{C\equiv C}$ moiety is substituted with $\!{}^{13}\mathrm{C}$.

